hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a system of three identical, non-interacting, spinless fermions, each of mass $m$. These particles are confined to a one-dimensional infinite potential well of length $L$. The potential $V(x)$ is defined as:
$$
V(x) = \begin{cases}
0 & \text{for } 0 < x < L \\
\infty & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
The single-particle energy eigenstates for a single particle in this potential are quantized. The corresponding energy eigenvalues are given by $E_n = \frac{n^2 \pi^2 \hbar^2}{2mL^2}$, where $n$ is a positive integer ($n=1, 2, 3, \ldots$) and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.

As the particles are identical fermions, the system must obey the Pauli exclusion principle. For spinless fermions, this principle simplifies to the condition that no two particles can occupy the same single-particle quantum state, which in this case is specified entirely by the quantum number $n$.

Assuming the fermions do not interact with each other, the total energy of the three-particle system is the sum of the energies of the individual particles. Your task is to determine the total energy of the ground state of this three-fermion system. Express your answer in terms of $m$, $L$, and $\hbar$.
